http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: An abstract class for specifying a person, organization or software entity that performs some action acting in some predefined role.
An agent performing some Role over a certain period of time (which may be unbounded).

An actual amino acid. This is not to contain information that helps identify an amino acid, but represents the amino acid being identified. Any information here, should be shared by all other representations of the amino acid.
An information object for storing data about an amino acid.
A property of some amino acid that was observed in a single Sample.

The best/selected identification of a specific Protein based on information in a PeptideIdentification. This means that a PeptideIdentification may have multiple Proteins that it identifies but that one of those proteins has been selected (identifiedBy) as the best identification.
The best SEQUEST DCn score for identifying an amino acid.
The best SEQUEST XCorr score for identifying an amino acid.
A deployment of some seagoing vessel on which one or more scientific objectives are studied.

The identifierScheme for a singular OPP dataset. The dataset itself is the realm in which other identifiers such as Station names, protein names, etc. are unique (but that may not be unqiue acorss other OPP datasets). This helps ensure that identifiers in a Dataset are not automatically assumed to be equivalent to each other.
A DatasetProfile defines the type of observations to be expected.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: Dataset Profile: Peptide Spectral Count Sum
Dataset Profile: Protein Total Spectral Count

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: The filter size in micons of the sampler.
The numerical score used to identified an Amino Acid using some scoring method.
A unique identifier attributeds to some thing within some realm or domain or scheme.
Information about an identifier that helps comprehend, reuse, or contextualize the Thing being identified. This could be a non-unique label or description.
A realm or domain in which a specific Identifier has a unqiue value from all the other possible Identifiers within that domain.
A peptide identified in a sample.

An information object where a dataset can store observations about an identified peptide in a sample. These observations may vary across many datasets claiming to identify the same peptide, so this entity serves as a way to store these observations separate from other peptide identifiation observations while still allowing these PeptideIdentification objeect to describe the same, singular Peptide.
Some property of a peptide identification that was observed in a single sample.
The sum of all spectra count.
The total spectral count of some identified peptide from a single sample.

The actual Protein being identified in datasets. This real-world Protein is identified by a single amino acid sequence regardless of variations across  ProteinIdentifications that describe this same, single Protein

A protein identification made based on information of a peptide identification. This entity serves as an information object used within a Dataset to identify and describe an actual Protein. Where a Protein has a single amino acid sequence that will not vary across datasets submitted to the OPP, th ereported protien names, molecular weights, etc may slightly vary across these datasets. ProteinIdentification exists so that individual datasets can report their findings and remain separate from other ProteinIdentification while still describing the exact same Protein with the same amino acid sequence.
A class of identifier schemes used to unqiuely identify proteins.
Some property of a protein identification that was observed in a single sample.
The total spectral count of some identified protein from a single sample.
A certain status, or position, played by some Agent that qualifies/contextualizes the actions performed by that Agent.
An identifier for a sample within a Dataset. The IdentifierScheme for this sample would be provides by the Dataset. See opp:definesIdentifierScheme
A generally agreed upon location at which sampling occurred. This agreement enables the comparison of collected data over different reference frames such as time.
absolute units of a peptide or protein identification measured in fmol/liter
The name given to the amino acid being identified by some identifying agent.
The amino acid chain, written as a string of characters, that identifies a specific amino acid.
The identifer for which this information object annotates
The best SEQUEST DCn score
The best SEQUEST XCorr score
A link to a visual drawing of the conceputal model for a certain class
The dataset conforms to the Dataset Profile. Meaning to presents the profile's expected observations.
Some label for a certain cruise on which an OPP Dataset was collected.
The IdentifierScheme defined by some Thing. In the case fo the OPP, a single Dataset defines an IdentifierScheme for its local identifiers.
The depth in meters where some sample was collected.
The conceptual model the describes this class can be found as an annotation of the following target class.
The AminoAcidChain being described by this information.
The actual Peptide being described by this information.
The actual Protein being described by this Protien information.
An AgentRole in which an Agent performs some Role on this particular Thing.
The size of the filter(s) being used during the sampling process. This could be a single value using schema:value property or a range of sizes using schema:minValue & schema:maxValue.
The score used to determine an amino acid's identification
Thee probability of the correctness/confidence of the identification
An Identifier with a known IdentifierScheme for some Thing.
An information record that annotated or further describes this Identifier.
The scheme in which this Identifier has a unique value.
The unique value in some IdentifierScheme
Role being performed by some Agent

The one, named or mutally agreed upon location at which Sampling occurred. This usually means a single coordinate at which sampling occurs depsite any variance in the location of the sensor at the time of measurement. This Station helps to normalize the intent of sampling at a certain location for cross-comparison between datasets.
The Thing on/in which an Agent performs some Role.
The Kegg Identifier for which this KeggPathway describes.
The maximum size of the filter used during sampling. Measured in microns.
The minimum size of a filter used during sampling. Mesaured in microns.
A protein's molecular weight measured in kiloDaltons
The NCBI Identifier for which this name describes.
An observation made about a single Sample for some identified amino acid.
The PeptideIdentification being asserted by the observer of some Sample.
The amino acid chain, written as a string of characters, that identifies a specific Peptide.
The Organization at which the acting Agent performed the Role
The Agent acting in some Role.
The Agent for which the performing Agent is acting in a certain Role.
An observation that will be present in the results.
The name given to the protein being identified by some identifying agent.
The amino acid chain, written as a string of characters, that identifies a specific Protein.
The observed spectral count for a single protein from a single sample
The existence of some Thing provides the ability for some Agent to perform this Role.
An observation made from a single Sample about an identified amino acid
An observation made from a single Sample about an identified peptide
An observation made from a single Sample about an identified protein
The sum of the +2, +3, +4 spectra counts.
The name of some Station.
A sample for which this Dataset stores observations results for.
